communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The absence of identification of wild poliovirus (WPV) type 3 in both human cases as well as in environmental samples for the past 2 years is a ray of optimism for the Global Polio Eradication Initiative. The objective of the polio eradication initiative is to eradicate all wild polioviruses. According to the Global Commission for the Certification of the Eradication of Poliomyelitis, "Certification of eradication will not be considered until a full 3 years have passed since the last detected and culture confirmed occurrence of a wild poliovirus." The Commission stated the need for surveillance for both cases of acute flaccid paralysis as well as for wild polioviruses, the latter through environmental sampling to document that the WPV is not circulating "silently". (Report of the 1st meeting of the Global Commission for the Certification of the Eradication of Poliomyelitis, Geneva, Switzerland 16-17 Feb 1995 WHO/EPI/GEN/95.6, http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/59821/1/WHO_EPI_GEN_95.6.pdf?ua=1).

As there are 3 wild polioviruses (WPV1, WPV2, and WPV3), all 3 types must meet the criteria for eradication -- 3 years without identification of the WPVs from human cases as well as in silent circulation. The last identification of WPV2 was in India in 1999 -- thus the WPV2 has been eradicated. If another year goes by without identification of WPV3, it will be a tremendous achievement towards the overall eradication initiative, with 2 out of the 3 WPV types meeting eradication criteria.

The obvious caution is that the last identified WPV3 in Pakistan was in a child in the FATA (Federally Administered Tribal Areas), an area with civil unrest, and a region where there are areas within that are not accessible for vaccination activities (and potentially surveillance activities) due to security concerns. The possibility that there is silent transmission of the WPV3 in those inaccessible areas is there. - Mod.MPP]

